======================================================================
PART 5: SIGN MECHANISM FOR D^{2n}
======================================================================

At p=3 mod 4: g(a) = chi(a)*sqrt(p), so g(a)*g(b) = chi(ab)*p
If D^{2n} deg-2 = R_n * g(a)*g(b) with R_n constant,
then sign(D^{2n} deg-2) = sign(R_n) * chi(ab)

For sign(h_hat) = chi(ab), we need sign(R_n) to be CONSISTENT
across all contributing D^{2n} terms (or the dominant one wins).

  p=7:
    D^2: R_1 =     0.000000, constant=True, sign=-
    D^4: R_2 =    -1.000000, constant=True, sign=-
    D^6: R_3 =    -6.750000, constant=True, sign=-
    D^8: R_4 =   -35.875000, constant=True, sign=-
    D^10: R_5 =  -178.281250, constant=True, sign=-

    Combined sign analysis:
    h_hat = sum_n w_n * R_n * g(a)*g(b) = [sum_n w_n * R_n] * chi(ab)*p
    Sign = sign(sum_n w_n * R_n)

  p=11:
    D^2: R_1 =    -0.000000, constant=True, sign=-
    D^4: R_2 =    -9.000000, constant=False, sign=-
    D^6: R_3 =  -143.250000, constant=False, sign=-
    D^8: R_4 = -1866.375000, constant=False, sign=-

    Combined sign analysis:
    h_hat = sum_n w_n * R_n * g(a)*g(b) = [sum_n w_n * R_n] * chi(ab)*p
    Sign = sign(sum_n w_n * R_n)

======================================================================
PART 6: OVERLAP WEIGHT = FEJER KERNEL OVERLAP
======================================================================

The overlap matrix W[k1,k2] = sum_{l=1}^m sin(2pi k1 l/p)*sin(2pi k2 l/p)
For p=3 mod 4, writing sin(kl) in terms of characters:
sin(kl) = Im(omega^{kl}) where omega = e^{2pi i/p}

The Fejer kernel F_m(t) = (1/m)|sum_{k=0}^{m-1} e^{ikt}|^2
is the spectral weight. Cycle overlaps are measured by F_m convolutions.

  p=7, m=3:
    W diagonal: 1.7500 (expect (p-1)/4 = 1.5000)
    W off-diag: min=-1.7500, max=0.0000

    W[k1,k2] = (1/2)[cos_sum(k1-k2) - cos_sum(k1+k2)]
    cos_sum(n) = sum_l cos(2pi*n*l/p) = m if p|n, else -1/2
    => W[k,k] = (1/2)[m - cos_sum(2k)] = (1/2)[(p-1)/2 + 1/2] = (2p-1)/4
    Predicted diagonal: 3.2500
    cos_sum(0) = 3.000000
    cos_sum(1) = -0.500000
    cos_sum(2) = -0.500000
    cos_sum(3) = -0.500000

  p=11, m=5:
    W diagonal: 2.7500 (expect (p-1)/4 = 2.5000)
    W off-diag: min=-2.7500, max=0.0000

    W[k1,k2] = (1/2)[cos_sum(k1-k2) - cos_sum(k1+k2)]
    cos_sum(n) = sum_l cos(2pi*n*l/p) = m if p|n, else -1/2
    => W[k,k] = (1/2)[m - cos_sum(2k)] = (1/2)[(p-1)/2 + 1/2] = (2p-1)/4
    Predicted diagonal: 5.2500
    cos_sum(0) = 5.000000
    cos_sum(1) = -0.500000
    cos_sum(2) = -0.500000
    cos_sum(5) = -0.500000

